    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the info. i think it might be a nutrient thing though because the yellowing is getting worse. if it is a nitrogen deficiency, how do i check if my soil pH is messed up and what should i do to fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you suspect a nutrient deficiency, checking the soil pH is a great place to start. You can use a soil testing kit to get an idea of your soil's pH levels. If the pH is too high or too low, it can affect the availability of nutrients for your plants. A pH range of 6.0 to 7.0 is ideal for tomatoes, but if your soil is too alkaline or acidic, it can cause nutrient deficiencies.\n\nTo fix a pH imbalance, you can adjust the soil pH by adding lime to raise it or sulfur to lower it. But, be careful not to overdo it, as this can also cause problems. It's a delicate balance, like a tightrope walk between the \"sweet spot\" and the \"danger zone.\" You don't want to end up with a pH that's too extreme, like a \"goblin's garden\" – you know, where the plants are struggling to survive.\n\nIf you're not sure how to adjust the pH, you can also consider getting a professional soil test done, which will provide a more accurate reading and recommendations for correction.",
